[Telangana](/Telangana), a [state](/States_and_union_territories_of_India) within the vast and often bewildering tapestry of [India](/India), finds its geographical anchor in the [south-central](/Southern_India) expanse of the [Indian subcontinent](/Indian_subcontinent). It rests upon the elevated plains of the [Deccan Plateau](/Deccan_Plateau), a geological formation that lends much of the region its distinctive character. Its territorial boundaries are defined by [Maharashtra](/Maharashtra) to the north, [Chhattisgarh](/Chhattisgarh) to the northeast, [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh) to the southeast – a state with which it shares a rather complicated past – and [Karnataka](/Karnataka) to the southwest. Statistically speaking, it holds the distinction of being the [eleventh largest state](/List_of_states_and_union_territories_of_India_by_area) in terms of land area and, according to the rather dated [2011 census](/2011_Census_of_India), the [twelfth most populated state in India](/List_of_states_and_union_territories_of_India_by_population). A relatively recent addition to the Indian federal structure, [Telangana](/Telangana) achieved its distinct statehood on 2 June 2014, when it was carved out from the northwestern portion of what was then known as [United Andhra Pradesh](/United_Andhra_Pradesh). Its capital, [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad), a city of considerable historical and economic significance, serves as its administrative heart.

The linguistic landscape of [Telangana](/Telangana) is dominated by [Telugu](/Telugu_language), which holds the status of one of the [classical languages of India](/Classical_languages_of_India). It is not only the most extensively spoken language but also the primary official language of the state. Complementing this, [Urdu](/Urdu) has been granted recognition as the second official language, a nod to the region's rich historical influences. Beyond these major languages, a fascinating array of tribal languages, including [Gondi](/Gondi_language), [Kolami](/Kolami), [Koya](/Koya_language), and [Lambadi](/Lambadi), are spoken in various pockets across the state, adding layers to its cultural mosaic.

Economically, [Telangana](/Telangana) has carved out a significant niche for itself, positioning as the [eighth largest](/List_of_Indian_states_and_union_territories_by_GDP) economy in [India](/India). For the financial year 2024–25, its [gross state domestic product](/Gross_state_domestic_product) (GSDP) reached an impressive ₹18 trillion (US$210 billion), demonstrating substantial economic momentum. The GSDP per capita, a measure of individual economic output, stood at ₹390,564 (US$4,600) for the same period, indicating a growing level of prosperity within its populace.

Beyond traditional sectors, [Telangana](/Telangana) has strategically positioned itself as a formidable hub for [IT software](/Information_technology) companies, a burgeoning [industrial sector](/Industrial_sector), and a robust [services sector](/Tertiary_sector_of_the_economy). It has also become a critical nerve center for numerous [Indian defence](/Defence_industry_of_India) [aerospace](/Aerospace) and research laboratories. This includes prominent institutions such as [Bharat Dynamics Limited](/Bharat_Dynamics_Limited), the [Defence Metallurgical Research Laboratory](/Defence_Metallurgical_Research_Laboratory), the sprawling [Defence Research and Development Organisation](/Defence_Research_and_Development_Organisation), and the specialized [Defence Research and Development Laboratory](/Defence_Research_and_Development_Laboratory), underscoring the state's strategic importance in national security and technological advancement.

## Etymology

The origin of the name "[Telangana](/Telangana)" is, predictably, a subject of scholarly debate and popular folklore, offering a choice between the sacred and the purely descriptive. One widely circulated theory posits that the name is a derivation from [Trilinga desha](/Trilinga_Kshetras), which translates rather grandly to the "land of three [lingas](/Lingam)." This theory suggests the region's spiritual significance, being home to three highly revered [Shaivite](/Shaivite) shrines. These include [Kaleshwaram](/Kaleshwaram), located within present-day [Telangana](/Telangana), alongside [Srisailam](/Srisailam) and [Draksharama](/Draksharama), both now situated in [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh). It's a neat narrative, tying the land to ancient religious geography.

However, historian [Jayadheer Tirumala Rao](/Jayadheer_Tirumala_Rao) offers a less mystical, but perhaps more linguistically rooted, alternative. He asserts that the name [Telangana](/Telangana) actually possesses [Gondi](/Gondi_people) origins. According to Rao, it stems from "Telangadh," a term in the [Gondi](/Gondi_language) language that simply means "south." He even points to evidence in "Gond script dating back to about 2,000 years," which, if true, would lend a rather ancient and indigenous flavor to the name, stripping away any divine connotations.

A tangible, early documented instance of a similar term appears in the 14th century CE, associated with [Malik Maqbul Tilangani](/Malik_Maqbul_Tilangani). The appellation "Tilangani" itself strongly implies his origins from [Telangana](/Telangana). This individual was not just any figure; he served as the formidable commander of the [Warangal Fort](/Warangal_Fort) (known in his time as Kataka Pāludu) before ascending to the influential position of [Wazir](/Vizier) (Minister) under the rule of [Firuz Shah Tughlaq](/Firuz_Shah_Tughlaq). This historical reference grounds the name in political and military prominence.

Further underscoring its historical presence, the 16th-century travel writer [Firishta](/Firishta) chronicled the region in his writings with a rather effusive description:

> During the just reign of [Ibrahim Kootb Shah](/Ibrahim_Quli_Qutb_Shah_Wali), Tulingana, like [Egypt](/Egypt), became the mart of the whole world. Merchants from Toorkistan, Arabia, and Persia resorted to it; and they met with such encouragement that they found in it inducements to return frequently. The greatest luxuries from foreign parts daily abounded at the king's hospitable board.

This passage paints a vivid picture of "Tulingana" as a vibrant, globally connected trade hub, a testament to its prosperity and significance during that era.

Over centuries, the word "Telinga" gradually evolved into "Telangana." This specific designation of "Telangana" emerged to delineate the predominantly [Telugu](/Telugu_people)-speaking areas of the erstwhile [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State) from its predominantly [Marathi](/Marathi_people)-speaking counterpart, [Marathwada](/Marathwada). Following the period when the [Asaf Jahi](/Asaf_Jahi) rulers ceded the [Seemandhra](/Andhra_Pradesh) region to the [British](/British_Empire), the remaining [Telugu](/Telugu_language)-speaking territory retained the name [Telangana](/Telangana), while the other ceded territories were subsequently referred to as the [Madras Presidency](/Madras_Presidency)'s [Circars](/Northern_Circars) and [Ceded Districts](/Ceded_Districts). This historical demarcation solidified the identity of [Telangana](/Telangana) as a distinct regional entity long before its modern statehood.

## History

The history of the [Telangana](/Telangana) region is a sprawling narrative, a testament to its enduring strategic and cultural importance on the [Indian subcontinent](/Indian_subcontinent). Throughout the epochs of antiquity and the often turbulent [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages), this land found itself integrated into a succession of powerful [Indian empires](/Indian_empires). These included the expansive [Maurya](/Maurya_Empire) dynasty, the influential [Satavahana dynasty](/Satavahana_dynasty), the lesser-known but significant [Vishnukundina dynasty](/Vishnukundina_dynasty), the formidable [Chalukya dynasty](/Chalukya_dynasty), the maritime prowess of the [Chola dynasty](/Chola_dynasty), the enduring legacy of the [Rashtrakuta dynasty](/Rashtrakuta_dynasty), the architectural brilliance of the [Kakatiya dynasty](/Kakatiya_dynasty), the far-reaching influence of the [Delhi Sultanate](/Delhi_Sultanate), the regional power of the [Bahmani Sultanate](/Bahmani_Sultanate), and finally, the opulent [Golconda Sultanate](/Qutb_Shahi_dynasty). Each left its indelible mark, layers of governance, culture, and conflict.

As history progressed into the 17th, 18th, and 19th centuries, the region transitioned through the powerful grip of the [Mughals](/Mughal_Empire) before settling under the distinct rule of the [Nizam of Hyderabad](/Nizam_of_Hyderabad). This era saw a unique blend of cultures and administrative structures. However, in 1823, a significant shift occurred when the Nizams, through a [subsidiary alliance](/Subsidiary_alliance) with the [British](/British_Empire), were compelled to cede the [Northern Circars](/Northern_Circars) (a region now part of [Coastal Andhra](/Coastal_Andhra)) and the [Ceded Districts](/Ceded_Districts) (encompassing [Rayalaseema](/Rayalaseema)) to [British India](/British_India). This strategic maneuver transformed the [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State) into a landlocked [princely state](/Princely_state), effectively encircled by British territories, diminishing its autonomy and sovereignty.

The advent of [Indian Independence](/Indian_Independence_Act_1947) in 1947 brought a new set of challenges. The [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State) initially resisted integration into the [Union of India](/Dominion_of_India), opting instead for independence. This stance, however, was short-lived. In 1948, the [Government of India](/Government_of_India) intervened with a decisive military operation, famously known as [Operation Polo](/Indian_annexation_of_Hyderabad), which led to the annexation of [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State). A further reorganization in 1956, under the [States Reorganisation Act, 1956](/States_Reorganisation_Act,_1956), saw the Telugu-speaking region of [Telangana](/Telangana) merged with the [Andhra State](/Andhra_State) to form the larger entity of [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh). This merger, however, was not universally welcomed. A persistent, peasant-driven [movement](/Telangana_movement) for separation from [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh) ignited in the early 1950s, gathering strength and momentum over decades, ultimately culminating in [Telangana](/Telangana) being granted its own statehood on 2 June 2014, fulfilling a long-held regional aspiration.

Historically, the venerable city of [Golconda](/Golconda), predating [Indian Independence](/Independence_of_India) within the former [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State), had cemented its reputation as a preeminent global center for diamond trading. Indeed, until the closing years of the 19th century, the [Golconda](/Golconda) market was the undisputed primary source for the world's most exquisite and substantial diamonds. Consequently, the term "[Golconda Diamonds](/Golconda_Diamonds)" became more than just a descriptor; it evolved into a powerful synecdoche, intrinsically linked with the very identity and prestige of [Golconda](/Golconda) itself.

### Early history

One of the earliest discernible political entities to emerge within the geographical confines of what is now [Telangana](/Telangana) was the ancient [Aśmaka](/A%C5%9Bmaka) (Assaka) Mahajanapada. This kingdom, a significant political and cultural force, flourished approximately between 700 BCE and 400 BCE. It held a unique distinction as the sole southern kingdom among the esteemed sixteen great [Mahajanapadas](/Mahajanapadas) of early Iron Age India, thereby securing a pivotal position in the subcontinent’s intricate historical and cultural narrative.

Both ancient [Buddhist texts](/Buddhist_texts) and the venerable [Puranas](/Puranas) consistently portray [Aśmaka](/A%C5%9Bmaka) as a flourishing and affluent kingdom. Its strategic location along the fertile banks of the [Godavari](/Godavari) River, positioned south of the formidable [Vindhya ranges](/Vindhya_Range), contributed significantly to its prosperity. The capital city of this illustrious kingdom, known as Podana—also referenced as Potali or Paudanyapura in various historical accounts—is, by the consensus of most contemporary scholars, identified with the modern-day town of [Bodhan](/Bodhan) in [Telangana](/Telangana). The consistent prominence of [Aśmaka](/A%C5%9Bmaka) in these early historical records serves as compelling evidence of the profound antiquity and deep cultural resonance that the [Telangana](/Telangana) region has held throughout millennia.

*   See also: [Maurya Empire](/Maurya_Empire)

Following the era of the [Mahajanapadas](/Mahajanapadas), the [Satavahana dynasty](/Satavahana_dynasty) rose to prominence, asserting its dominance over this region from approximately 230 BCE to 220 CE. Originating from the fertile lands nestled between the mighty [Godavari](/Godavari) and [Krishna](/Krishna_River) rivers, their power base was initially established at Amaravathi and Dharanikota. After the eventual decline of the [Satavahanas](/Satavahana_dynasty), a succession of diverse dynasties stepped into the void, each leaving its own imprint on the landscape. These included the [Vakataka](/Vakataka_dynasty), [Vishnukundina](/Vishnukundina_dynasty), [Chalukya](/Chalukya_dynasty), [Rashtrakuta](/Rashtrakuta_Dynasty), and [Western Chalukya](/Western_Chalukya_Empire) dynasties, each contributing to the rich historical tapestry of the area.

### Medieval period

*   Main article: [Kakatiya dynasty](/Kakatiya_dynasty)

![Ramagiri Fort ruins at Begampet in Peddapalli district is an ancient fort initially built by the Sathavahanas and modified many times by other dynasties until the 16th century.](/Ramagiri_Fort)
*The enduring ruins of [Ramagiri Fort](/Ramagiri_Fort) at Begampet in [Peddapalli district](/Peddapalli_district) stand as a stark reminder of successive historical layers. Initially a stronghold of the [Satavahanas](/Satavahana_dynasty), it underwent numerous modifications by various dynasties, its stones bearing witness to centuries of change until the 16th century.*

![Kota Gullu, temple ruins built in the 12th century by Kakatiyas at Ghanpur, Mulug in Warangal district](/Kota_Gullu)
*[Kota Gullu](/Kota_Gullu), a collection of temple ruins, quietly attest to the architectural prowess of the [Kakatiyas](/Kakatiyas), having been constructed in the 12th century at Ghanpur, Mulug, within what was once the expansive [Warangal district](/Warangal_district).*

The [Telangana](/Telangana) region truly experienced a period often referred to as its "golden age" under the formidable and culturally significant reign of the [Kakatiya dynasty](/Kakatiya_dynasty). This powerful dynasty held sway over the majority of the present-day [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh) and [Telangana](/Telangana) from 1083 to 1323 CE, establishing a legacy of architectural marvels and sophisticated governance. Among its most distinguished rulers were [Rudrama Devi](/Rudrama_Devi), a queen who defied patriarchal norms to rule with exceptional skill, and [Prataparudra II](/Prataparudra_II), whose reign marked both the zenith and the eventual decline of the dynasty. The [Kakatiya](/Kakatiya_dynasty)'s strength began to wane following the devastating assault by [Malik Kafur](/Malik_Kafur) in 1309. The dynasty ultimately faced its dissolution after the decisive defeat of [Prataparudra](/Prataparudra_II) at the hands of the forces of [Muhammad bin Tughluq](/Muhammad_bin_Tughluq) in 1323, marking the end of an era.

![Golconda Fort](/Golconda_Fort)
*The imposing [Golconda Fort](/Golconda_Fort) – a silent sentinel of empires past.*

Following the [Kakatiya](/Kakatiya_dynasty) collapse, the region subsequently fell under the administrative control of the distant [Delhi Sultanate](/Delhi_Sultanate) in the 14th century, a period of shifting power dynamics. This was later succeeded by the rise of the [Bahmani Sultanate](/Bahmani_Sultanate), which established a more localized, yet still formidable, presence. It was from within this context that [Quli Qutb Mulk](/Quli_Qutb_Mulk), a governor entrusted with the administration of [Golconda](/Golconda), famously declared his independence from the [Bahmani Sultanate](/Bahmani_Sultanate). In 1518, he founded the illustrious [Qutb Shahi dynasty](/Qutb_Shahi_dynasty), which brought a new era of prosperity and cultural flourishing to the region. However, even this powerful dynasty eventually succumbed to larger forces. On 21 September 1687, the [Golconda Sultanate](/Qutb_Shahi_dynasty) was forcibly brought under the dominion of the [Mughal emperor Aurangzeb](/Aurangzeb), following a protracted and brutal [year-long siege](/Siege_of_Golconda) of the iconic [Golconda fort](/Golconda).

During the nascent years of the seventeenth century, [Telangana](/Telangana) was home to a remarkably robust and sophisticated cotton-weaving industry. This sector was not merely a local enterprise; it produced substantial quantities of cotton, catering both to significant domestic consumption and a thriving export market. The artisans of the region were renowned for their skill, producing high-quality plain and intricately patterned cloth, including fine [muslin](/Muslin) and durable calico, which were highly sought after.

In 1712, a pivotal appointment was made when [Qamar-ud-din Khan](/Qamar-ud-din_Khan,_Asif_Jah_I) was designated by the emperor [Farrukhsiyar](/Farrukhsiyar) as the viceroy of [Deccan](/Deccan), bestowed with the grand title Nizam-ul-Mulk, signifying "Administrator of the Realm." His tenure, however, was interrupted when he was recalled to Delhi, and Mubariz Khan assumed the viceregal position. Not one to relinquish power easily, [Qamar-ud-din Khan](/Qamar-ud-din_Khan,_Asif_Jah_I) orchestrated a decisive victory over Mubariz Khan in 1724, thereby reclaiming control of the [Deccan suba](/Deccan_suba). This victory marked the establishment of an autonomous province, effectively independent of direct [Mughal](/Mughal_Empire) control, though still nominally within its empire. He adopted the regal name [Asif Jah](/Asif_Jah_1), thus founding what would become the enduring [Asaf Jahi dynasty](/Asaf_Jahi_dynasty). He christened the territory [Hyderabad Deccan](/Hyderabad_State). Subsequent rulers of this lineage consistently bore the title Nizam ul-Mulk and became famously known as the [Asif Jahi Nizams](/Asaf_Jahi_dynasty) or, more simply, the [Nizams of Hyderabad](/Nizam_of_Hyderabad). It is worth noting that despite their autonomy, the [Hyderabad Nizams](/Nizam_of_Hyderabad) were compelled to maintain a tributary relationship with the [Marathas](/Marathas) following a series of military defeats, paying an annual *chauth* in exchange for retaining their dominion. The [Medak](/Medak_Gulshanabad_Division) and [Warangal](/Warangal_Division) divisions of [Telangana](/Telangana) formed an integral part of their expansive realm.

![Telangana was the seat of numerous dynasties. The Chowmahalla Palace was home to the Nizams of Hyderabad.](/Chowmahalla_Palace)
*[Telangana](/Telangana), a land that has served as the coveted seat for a multitude of dynasties, ultimately saw the magnificent [Chowmahalla Palace](/Chowmahalla_Palace) become the opulent residence for the [Nizams of Hyderabad](/Nizam_of_Hyderabad) – a fitting stage for their elaborate reigns.*

![Hyderabad State in 1909](/Hyderabad_State)
*[Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State) in 1909 – a snapshot of a princely domain, before the world decided it needed to be reorganized.*

The political landscape grew increasingly tumultuous after the demise of [Asif Jah I](/Asif_Jah_1) in 1748. His passing ignited a fierce struggle for succession among his sons, a power vacuum eagerly exploited by opportunistic neighboring states and the ever-present, calculating colonial foreign forces. By 1769, the city of [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad) had been formally designated as the capital of the [Nizams](/Nizam_of_Hyderabad), solidifying its administrative and symbolic importance. A critical turning point arrived when the Nizam [Nasir-ud-dawlah, Asaf Jah IV](/Nasir-ud-dawlah,_Asaf_Jah_IV) reluctantly affixed his signature to the infamous [subsidiary alliance](/Subsidiary_alliance) with the [British](/British_Empire) in 1799. This agreement, a common colonial tactic, effectively stripped the state of its control over crucial matters of defense and foreign affairs, rendering it a protectorate.

Initially, all the [Telugu](/Telugu_language)-speaking territories that now constitute present-day [Telangana](/Telangana), [Coastal Andhra](/Coastal_Andhra), and [Rayalaseema](/Rayalaseema) were unified under the dominion of [Asaf Jahi I](/Asif_Jah_1). However, the second monarch in the lineage, [Nizam Ali Khan, Asaf Jah II](/Nizam_Ali_Khan,_Asaf_Jah_II) (who reigned from 1762 to 1803), entered into the Treaty of Subsidiary Alliance with the British in 1798. This agreement placed the rulers under severe financial strain, as the state was obligated to remit vast sums, specifically lakhs of rupees annually, to the [British East India Company](/British_East_India_Company) for the upkeep of foreign troops stationed within its borders.

The Nizam’s government, finding itself in an untenable financial position, resorted to extensive borrowing from [Palmer and Company](/Palmer_and_Company) during the first half of the 19th century, accumulating debts it was ultimately incapable of repaying. In a rather convenient turn of events for the British, the [East India Company](/British_East_India_Company) (EIC) stepped in to settle these outstanding debts to the bank. In return for this "generosity," the EIC proceeded to annex the regions that are now known as [Coastal Andhra](/Coastal_Andhra) and [Rayalaseema](/Rayalaseema) from the [Nizams](/Nizam_of_Hyderabad). These territories were subsequently referred to as the [Circars](/Northern_Circars) (a term denoting regions sold to British lords) and the [Ceded Districts](/Ceded_Districts), respectively.

Thus, [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State) was relegated to the status of a [princely state](/Princely_state), existing within the larger framework of the [presidencies and provinces of British India](/Presidencies_and_provinces_of_British_India). Its once vast autonomy was now circumscribed by British paramountcy.

A particularly devastating natural calamity struck in 1787, when heavy flooding claimed the lives of over 20,000 individuals across [Telangana](/Telangana). This disaster was tragically compounded by a subsequent plague, which, with ruthless efficiency, wiped out an additional estimated 10,656 people in the state, leaving a profound scar on the region's population and collective memory.

### Modern period

When [India finally achieved independence](/Independence_of_India) from the British Empire in 1947, the [Nizam of Hyderabad](/Nizam_of_Hyderabad) harbored ambitions of maintaining his state's independence, rather than integrating into the newly formed [Indian Union](/Dominion_of_India). This aspiration, however, was swiftly and decisively quashed by the [Government of India](/Government_of_India), which, on 17 September 1948, annexed [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State) through a military intervention famously dubbed [Operation Polo](/Operation_Polo). Following this integration, a civil servant named [M. K. Vellodi](/M._K._Vellodi) was appointed as the inaugural chief minister of [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State) on 26 January 1950. His administration largely relied on English-educated bureaucrats, many of whom hailed from the [Madras](/Madras_State) and [Bombay](/Bombay_State) states. These individuals were well-versed in the British systems of administration, a stark contrast to the bureaucrats of the former [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State) who operated under a fundamentally different framework. Consequently, the official language of the state underwent a significant shift, transitioning from [Urdu](/Urdu) to [English](/English_language), further emphasizing the break from the past.

By 1952, a significant democratic milestone was reached when [Burgula Ramakrishna Rao](/Burgula_Ramakrishna_Rao) was elected as the chief minister of the [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State) in its first-ever democratic election. This period, however, was also characterized by intense and often violent agitations. A segment of [Telangana](/Telangana) natives passionately demanded the repatriation of bureaucrats from the [Madras State](/Madras_State) and the implementation of a rule exclusively by the indigenous people, or *mulkis*, of [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad). Following [Dr. Burgula Ramakrishna Rao](/Burgula_Ramakrishna_Rao)'s resignation from his post, Syed Alam Sharjil was elected as the chief minister, inheriting a politically charged environment.

*   Main article: [Telangana Rebellion](/Telangana_Rebellion)

The [Telangana Rebellion](/Telangana_Rebellion) was a tumultuous and profoundly impactful [peasant revolt](/List_of_peasant_revolts), significantly bolstered and supported by [communists](/Communist) in the region. This uprising originated in the [Telangana](/Telangana) areas of the [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State), unfolding between 1946 and 1951, and was primarily spearheaded by the [Communist Party of India](/Communist_Party_of_India) (CPI).

The initial sparks of the revolt were ignited in the [Nalgonda district](/Nalgonda_district), where peasants rose up against the entrenched [feudal](/Feudalism) lords, predominantly from the powerful [Reddy](/Reddy) and [Velama](/Velama_(caste)) castes. The movement rapidly gained traction, spreading with fervent intensity to the neighboring [Warangal](/Warangal_district) and [Bidar](/Bidar_district) districts. Peasant farmers and laborers, long suffering under oppressive conditions, rebelled against the local feudal landlords, known as *[jagirdars](/Jagir)* and *[deshmukhs](/Deshmukh)*. Their grievances soon escalated, turning their ire against the overarching authority of [the Nizam Osman Ali Khan](/Osman_Ali_Khan,_Asaf_Jah_VII). The violent phase of this pivotal movement ultimately concluded following the [Government of India](/Government_of_India)'s decisive military intervention, [Operation Polo](/Operation_Polo). Subsequent to 1951, the [CPI](/Communist_Party_of_India) strategically recalibrated its approach, shifting towards a more moderate political strategy aimed at integrating communism within the established framework of [Indian democracy](/Democracy_in_India).

In December 1953, the [States Reorganisation Commission](/States_Reorganisation_Commission) (SRC) was formally constituted, tasked with the monumental responsibility of redrawing state boundaries primarily along linguistic lines. This initiative led to an agreement, reached on 20 February 1956, between the leaders of [Telangana](/Telangana) and [Andhra](/Andhra_State), which proposed the merger of the two regions. This merger was predicated upon explicit promises to safeguard [Telangana](/Telangana)'s distinct interests, a commitment that would later become a source of contention. Following this [Gentlemen's agreement](/Gentlemen%27s_agreement_of_Andhra_Pradesh_(1956)), the central government proceeded to establish the unified state of [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh) on 1 November 1956. A subsequent administrative adjustment, G.O 553 of 1959 from the newly united [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh) state, saw two revenue divisions—[Bhadrachalam](/Bhadrachalam) from [East Godavari](/East_Godavari) and [Aswaraopeta](/Aswaraopeta) from West Godavari—transferred to [Khammam](/Khammam_district) for enhanced administrative convenience.

*   Main article: [Telangana movement](/Telangana_movement)

The merger of [Telangana](/Telangana) and [Andhra](/Andhra_State) was, predictably, not the final word. There had been several persistent movements advocating for the revocation of this merger, with significant agitations manifesting in 1969, 1972, and again in 2009. The demand for a distinct state of [Telangana](/Telangana) truly gained formidable momentum in the 21st century, largely propelled by the determined initiative of [Kalvakuntla Chandrashekhar Rao](/Kalvakuntla_Chandrashekhar_Rao), the leader of the [Bharat Rashtra Samithi](/Bharat_Rashtra_Samithi). This movement further consolidated its strength with the active involvement of the [Telangana Political Joint Action Committee](/Telangana_Joint_Action_Committee) (TJAC), which effectively brought together various political leaders representing the [Telangana](/Telangana) area. On 9 December 2009, the [Government of India](/Government_of_India) publicly announced its intention to initiate the process for the formation of the [Telangana](/Telangana) state. This declaration, however, immediately triggered vehement protests led by residents in the [Coastal Andhra](/Coastal_Andhra) and [Rayalseema](/Rayalseema) regions, compelling the government to place the decision on an indefinite hold by 23 December 2009.

Despite the temporary suspension, the movement for statehood persisted with unwavering resolve, particularly within [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad) and other districts of [Telangana](/Telangana). This period was marked by profound societal upheaval, including hundreds of reported suicides—each a tragic testament to the depth of the sentiment—along with widespread strikes, relentless protests, and significant disruptions to public life, all demanding the unequivocal grant of separate statehood.

*   See also: [Andhra Pradesh Reorganisation Act, 2014](/Andhra_Pradesh_Reorganisation_Act,_2014)

On 30 July 2013, after much deliberation and political maneuvering, the Congress Working Committee unanimously adopted a resolution recommending the formation of a separate [Telangana](/Telangana) state. This recommendation navigated various legislative stages before the bill was finally introduced in the [Parliament of India](/Parliament_of_India) in February 2014. Subsequently, in February 2014, the [Andhra Pradesh Reorganisation Act, 2014](/Andhra_Pradesh_Reorganisation_Act,_2014) bill was successfully passed by the [Parliament of India](/Parliament_of_India), formally paving the way for the creation of [Telangana](/Telangana) state. This new entity was to comprise ten districts carved out from the northwestern portion of [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh). The bill received the requisite assent of the [president](/President_of_India) and was officially published in the [Gazette](/The_Gazette_of_India) on 1 March 2014, making it law.

The state of [Telangana](/Telangana) was officially inaugurated on 2 June 2014, marking a historic moment for the region. In the elections that preceded this formation, [Kalvakuntla Chandrashekar Rao](/Kalvakuntla_Chandrashekar_Rao), leading the [Bharat Rashtra Samithi](/Bharat_Rashtra_Samithi) party, secured a decisive majority and was subsequently elected as the first chief minister of [Telangana](/Telangana). As part of the reorganisation, [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad) was designated to serve as the joint capital for both [Telangana](/Telangana) and [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh) for a transitional period. The understanding was that within a decade, [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad) would become the exclusive capital of [Telangana](/Telangana), necessitating the selection of a new capital for [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh). True to this arrangement, [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh) ultimately chose [Amaravati](/Amaravati) as its new capital, initiating the relocation of its secretariat in 2016 and its legislature in 2017, formally concluding the shared capital arrangement.

## Geography

*   See also: [List of cities and towns in Telangana](/List_of_cities_and_towns_in_Telangana)

![Telangana and its neighbours](/Telangana_and_its_neighbours)
*Telangana and its neighbors – a geographical context, for those who appreciate boundaries.*

[Telangana](/Telangana), like an ancient sentinel, is geographically positioned on the vast [Deccan Plateau](/Deccan_Plateau), specifically within the central expanse of the eastern seaboard of the [Indian Peninsula](/Indian_Peninsula). It encompasses a considerable land area of 112,077 square kilometers (43,273 sq mi), a substantial portion of the subcontinent. The region's hydrology is primarily shaped by two of [India](/India)'s most significant rivers: the [Godavari River](/Godavari_River) and the [Krishna River](/Krishna_River). Approximately 79% of the [Godavari River](/Godavari_River)'s catchment area and about 69% of the [Krishna River](/Krishna_River)'s catchment area lie within [Telangana](/Telangana)'s borders, yet, despite this impressive drainage, a significant portion of its land remains arid, a paradox that speaks to the challenges of water management. In addition to these behemoths, [Telangana](/Telangana) is also traversed and sustained by several minor, but locally vital, rivers such as the [Bhima](/Bhima_River), the [Maner](/Maner_River), the [Manjira](/Manjira_River), the [Musi](/Musi_River_(India)), and the [Tungabhadra](/Tungabhadra_River), each contributing to the regional ecosystem.

The state experiences an annual rainfall that varies significantly across its expanse, ranging from 900 to 1500mm in the northern regions of [Telangana](/Telangana) and a somewhat drier 700 to 900mm in the southern parts, all primarily influenced by the powerful southwest [monsoons](/Monsoon). This climatic variation, combined with geological diversity, has endowed [Telangana](/Telangana) with a rich assortment of soil types. These include the characteristic red sandy loams, locally known as Chalaka, the more granular Red loamy sands (Dubba), lateritic soils, areas affected by salinity, fertile alluvial soils, various shallow to medium black soils, and notably, very deep black cotton soils. This mosaic of soil types is remarkably conducive to the cultivation of a diverse range of agricultural produce, from a variety of fruits like mangoes, oranges, and bananas, to essential crops such as coconut, sugarcane, paddy, and an array of vibrant flower crops, showcasing the state's agricultural potential.

### Climate

[Telangana](/Telangana) is largely characterized as a semi-arid region, enduring a climate that is predominantly hot and dry for much of the year. The summer months commence their relentless advance in March, reaching their scorching zenith by mid-April, with average high temperatures consistently hovering in the rather uncomfortable 37–38 °C (99–100 °F) range. A brief, yet vital, respite arrives with the onset of the [monsoon](/Monsoon) season in June, which typically persists until late-September, delivering approximately 755 mm (29.7 inches) of much-needed precipitation. Following the monsoon, a relatively dry and mild winter period sets in, spanning from late November to early February, characterized by significantly reduced humidity and average temperatures that settle into a more agreeable 22–23 °C (72–73 °F) range, offering a welcome reprieve from the intense heat.

### Ecology

The [Central Deccan Plateau dry deciduous forests](/Central_Deccan_Plateau_dry_deciduous_forests) ecoregion, with its distinct flora and fauna, encompasses a significant portion of the state, including the metropolitan area of [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad). The characteristic vegetation of this region is defined by woodlands dominated by species such as [Hardwickia binata](/Hardwickia_binata) and [Albizia amara](/Albizia_amara), forming a resilient ecosystem adapted to the dry conditions. Regrettably, over 80% of the original forest cover within this ecoregion has been systematically cleared, a consequence of relentless expansion for agriculture, unsustainable timber harvesting practices, or the demands of cattle grazing. Despite this extensive degradation, substantial and vital blocks of forest still manage to persist, notably within the protected expanse of the [Nagarjunsagar-Srisailam Tiger Reserve](/Nagarjunsagar-Srisailam_Tiger_Reserve) and other scattered remnants. In contrast, the more humid [Eastern Highlands moist deciduous forests](/Eastern_Highlands_moist_deciduous_forests) are found covering the majestic [Eastern Ghats](/Eastern_Ghats) mountain range, which stretches across the eastern part of the state, showcasing a distinct and richer biodiversity influenced by higher moisture levels.

### National parks and sanctuaries

[Telangana](/Telangana) has, against all odds, managed to preserve pockets of its natural heritage, housing three designated [National Parks](/List_of_national_parks_of_India). These include the [Kasu Brahmananda Reddy National Park](/Kasu_Brahmananda_Reddy_National_Park) located conveniently within [Hyderabad district](/Hyderabad_District,_India), and both the [Mahavir Harina Vanasthali National Park](/Mahavir_Harina_Vanasthali_National_Park) and [Mrugavani National Park](/Mrugavani_National_Park), which are situated in the adjacent [Ranga Reddy district](/Ranga_Reddy_district), offering green oases amidst urban sprawl.

![Indian peafowl (Pavo cristatus) near Hyderabad](/Pavo_cristatus)
*An [Indian peafowl](/Pavo_cristatus) near [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad) – a splash of unexpected color in an often-monochrome existence.*

Beyond these national parks, [Telangana](/Telangana) is also home to a network of crucial wildlife sanctuaries, each playing its part in conservation. These include the [Eturunagaram Wildlife Sanctuary](/Eturunagaram_Wildlife_Sanctuary) and the [Pakhal Wildlife Sanctuary](/Pakhal_Lake) in [Warangal District](/Warangal_District), the vital [Kawal Tiger Reserve](/Kawal_Wildlife_Sanctuary) and [Pranahita Wildlife Sanctuary](/Pranahita_Wildlife_Sanctuary) in [Adilabad district](/Adilabad_district), the [Kinnerasani Wildlife Sanctuary](/Kinnerasani_Wildlife_Sanctuary) nestled in [Khammam district](/Khammam_district), the avian haven of [Manjira Wildlife Sanctuary](/Manjira_Wildlife_Sanctuary) in [Medak district](/Medak_district), the expansive [Nagarjunsagar-Srisailam Tiger Reserve](/Nagarjunsagar-Srisailam_Tiger_Reserve) which spans both [Nalgonda](/Nalgonda_District) and [Mahbubnagar districts](/Mahbubnagar_district), the [Pocharam Wildlife Sanctuary](/Pocharam_Wildlife_Sanctuary) covering parts of [Medak](/Medak_district) and Nizamabad districts, and finally, the [Shivaram Wildlife Sanctuary](/Shivaram_Wildlife_Sanctuary) in [Karimnagar district](/Karimnagar_district). These protected areas serve as critical refuges for the state's diverse fauna.

A particularly fascinating aspect of the local ecology and culture are the [Sacred groves](/Sacred_groves_of_India), which are essentially small, often ancient, pockets of forest meticulously preserved by local communities. These groves serve a dual purpose: they act as vital sanctuaries for the indigenous flora and fauna, maintaining biodiversity, and simultaneously hold profound cultural and religious significance. While some of these sacred groves are fortunate enough to be encompassed within larger protected areas, such as the Kadalivanam within the [Nagarjunsagar–Srisailam Tiger Reserve](/Nagarjunsagar-Srisailam_Tiger_Reserve), the majority stand as independent, cherished natural monuments. [Telangana](/Telangana) currently boasts 65 such sacred groves, distributed across its districts: two in [Adilabad district](/Adilabad_district), thirteen in [Hyderabad district](/Hyderabad_district,_India), four in [Karimnagar district](/Karimnagar_district), four in [Khammam district](/Khammam_district), nine in [Mahbubnagar district](/Mahbubnagar_district), four in [Medak district](/Medak_district), nine in [Nalgonda district](/Nalgonda_district), ten in [Ranga Reddy district](/Ranga_Reddy_district), and three in [Warangal district](/Warangal_district). They are living testaments to a long-standing tradition of environmental stewardship, often rooted in spiritual reverence.

## Demographics

*   See also: [List of cities and towns in Telangana](/List_of_cities_and_towns_in_Telangana), [Demographics of Telangana](/Demographics_of_Telangana), and [List of districts of Telangana](/List_of_districts_of_Telangana)

### Language

![Languages spoken by district Telugu 30–40% 40–50% 60–70% 70–80% 80–90% 90–100%](/Languages_spoken_by_district)
*A rather telling map depicting the distribution of languages by district. One can observe the pervasive dominance of [Telugu](/Telugu_language), with other linguistic pockets making their presence known, a subtle reminder that homogeneity is often an illusion.*

*   See also: [Telugu language](/Telugu_language)

Languages of Telangana (2011)
*   [Telugu](/Telugu_language) (75.5%) – The undisputed majority, setting the linguistic tone.
*   [Urdu](/Urdu) (12.3%) – A significant minority, reflecting a rich historical confluence.
*   [Lambadi](/Lambadi) (5.55%) – A vibrant tribal language, keeping cultural threads alive.
*   [Marathi](/Marathi_language) (1.77%) – A border influence, a reminder that lines on a map are often arbitrary.
*   [Hindi](/Hindi) (1.52%) – The national language, finding its footing in urban centers.
*   Others (3.33%) – A collection of diverse voices, refusing to be categorized neatly.

[Telugu](/Telugu_language), a language that has earned its rightful place among the [classical languages of India](/Classical_languages_of_India), serves as the official language of [Telangana](/Telangana). Complementing this, [Urdu](/Urdu) holds the status of the state's second official language, a recognition that speaks volumes about the region's historical depth and cultural intermingling. Approximately 75% of [Telangana](/Telangana)'s population communicates in [Telugu](/Telugu_language), while a notable 12% speaks [Urdu](/Urdu). Prior to 1948, [Urdu](/Urdu) was not merely a language but the official language of the erstwhile [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State). Due to a conspicuous scarcity of [Telugu](/Telugu_language)-language educational institutions during that period, [Urdu](/Urdu) consequently became the language of the educated elite within [Telangana](/Telangana), a marker of social standing and access to knowledge.

However, the political landscape shifted dramatically after 1948, when [Hyderabad State](/Hyderabad_State) was integrated into the nascent [Republic of India](/Republic_of_India). With this, [Telugu](/Telugu_language) ascended to become the language of government, and its widespread introduction as the [medium of instruction](/Medium_of_instruction) in schools and colleges gradually led to a decline in the use of [Urdu](/Urdu) among non-[Hyderabadi Muslims](/Hyderabadi_Muslims). Today, both [Telugu](/Telugu_language) and [Urdu](/Urdu) find practical application across various state services, a testament to their continued relevance. For instance, the [Telangana Legislature](/Telangana_Legislature) website thoughtfully offers both [Telugu](/Telugu_language) and [Urdu](/Urdu) versions, ensuring broader accessibility. Similarly, the [Hyderabad metro](/Hyderabad_Metro) prominently features both languages on its station names and directional signs, alongside [English](/English_language) and [Hindi](/Hindi), reflecting the city's multicultural fabric. The specific dialect of [Urdu](/Urdu) spoken in [Telangana](/Telangana) is referred to as [Hyderabadi Urdu](/Hyderabadi_Urdu), which itself is a regional variant within the broader family of [Dakhini](/Deccani_Language) Urdu dialects prevalent in [South India](/South_India). While it remains the spoken language for most [Hyderabadi Muslims](/Hyderabadi_Muslims), its literary form has largely faded, with standard [Urdu](/Urdu) now typically employed in formal writing. [Hindi](/Hindi) is primarily spoken in [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad), as well as in other urban centers like [Warangal](/Warangal). [Lambadi](/Lambadi), a language exhibiting ties to [Rajasthani dialects](/Rajasthani_languages), is heard across the state, particularly among nomadic communities. [Marathi](/Marathi_language) speakers form a predominant linguistic group in regions bordering [Maharashtra](/Maharashtra), especially within the historical [Adilabad district](/Adilabad_district). Conversely, [Kannada](/Kannada) is spoken by significant minority populations along certain stretches of the [Karnataka](/Karnataka) border. The old [Adilabad district](/Adilabad_district) also hosts a substantial number of speakers of various tribal languages, including [Gondi](/Gondi_language) and [Kolami](/Kolami_language), while [Koya](/Koya_language) is a language spoken by considerable numbers in [Bhadradi Kothagudem district](/Bhadradri_Kothagudem_district) and along the [Chhattisgarh](/Chhattisgarh) border, illustrating the rich linguistic diversity that underpins [Telangana](/Telangana)'s identity.

In a recent assessment, [Telangana](/Telangana) managed to secure the eighth position in the Fiscal Health Index (FHI) 2025, achieving a score of 43.6. One might interpret this as "not bad," given the general state of things.

### Religion and culture

*   Religion in Telangana (2011)
    *   [Hinduism](/Hinduism) (85.1%) – The predominant faith, shaping much of the cultural landscape.
    *   [Islam](/Hyderabadi_Muslims) (12.7%) – A significant and deeply rooted presence, particularly in [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad).
    *   [Christianity](/Telugu_Christians) (1.27%) – A minority, yet active, community.
    *   [Buddhism](/Buddhism) (0.09%) – A faint echo of a once-flourishing past.
    *   [Sikhism](/Sikhism) (0.09%) – A small, yet distinct, community.
    *   [Jainism](/Jainism) (0.08%) – Another ancient faith, holding a quiet presence.
    *   Other (0.01%) – The truly unique, or simply those who defy categorization.
    *   Not stated (0.68%) – Because some prefer to keep their spiritual inclinations private, which is, frankly, understandable.

According to the [2011 census](/2011_Census_of_India), the spiritual bedrock of [Telangana](/Telangana) is overwhelmingly [Hinduism](/Hinduism), with adherents constituting a substantial 85.1% of the state's total population. [Muslims](/Islam) form a significant and historically influential minority, accounting for 12.7%, while [Christians](/Christians) represent a smaller, yet notable, demographic at 1.3%.

The state is dotted with a rich tapestry of religious edifices, serving as focal points for various faiths. Among the most revered [Hindu](/Hinduism) sites are the majestic [Lakshmi Narasimha Temple](/Lakshmi_Narasimha_Temple,_Yadadri) in [Yadadri Bhuvanagiri district](/Yadadri_Bhuvanagiri_district), the ancient [Bhadrakali Temple](/Bhadrakali_Temple) and [Govinda Rajula Gutta](/Govinda_Rajula_Gutta) in [Warangal](/Warangal), the venerable [Alampur Jogulamba Temple](/Alampur_Jogulamba_Temple) in [Jogulamba Gadwal district](/Jogulamba_Gadwal_district), the [Kondagattu Anjaneya Swamy Temple](/Kondagattu_Anjaneya_Swamy_Temple) in [Jagtial District](/Jagtial_District), and the revered Lord Shiva temple in [Vemulawada](/Vemulawada,_Rajanna_Sircilla_district) of [Rajanna Sircilla district](/Rajanna_Sircilla_district). The grand [Makkah Masjid](/Makkah_Masjid,_Hyderabad) in [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad) stands as a monumental testament to [Islamic](/Islam) heritage. For [Christians](/Christians), the stately [Medak Cathedral](/Medak_Cathedral) in [Medak District](/Medak_District) serves as a significant place of worship. Historically, [Buddhism](/Buddhism) also thrived in this region, leaving behind numerous *Aramams* (monasteries) that whisper tales of a bygone era.

The distinct culinary traditions of [Hyderabadi cuisine](/Hyderabadi_cuisine) and the intricate artistic expressions of [Kakatiya architecture](/Kakatiya_architecture), both deeply embedded in [Telangana](/Telangana)'s cultural fabric, have garnered international recognition. [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad) itself has been designated a [UNESCO creative city of gastronomy](/City_of_Gastronomy), a testament to its rich culinary heritage, while the [Ramappa Temple](/Ramappa_Temple) stands proudly as a [UNESCO World Heritage Site](/World_Heritage_Site), showcasing the architectural brilliance of the [Kakatiya](/Kakatiya_dynasty) period.

The cultural epicenters of [Telangana](/Telangana), namely [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad) and [Warangal](/Warangal), are rightly celebrated for their immense wealth of renowned historical structures. These include the already mentioned [Ramappa Temple](/Ramappa_Temple) (a [UNESCO World Heritage Site](/World_Heritage_Site)), the iconic [Charminar](/Charminar) that defines [Hyderabad](/Hyderabad)'s skyline, the regal [Qutb Shahi Tombs](/Qutb_Shahi_Tombs), the opulent [Falaknuma Palace](/Falaknuma_Palace), the sprawling [Chowmahalla Palace](/Chowmahalla_Palace), the formidable [Warangal Fort](/Warangal_Fort), the intricately carved [Kakatiya Kala Thoranam](/Kakatiya_Kala_Thoranam), the impressive [Thousand Pillar Temple](/Thousand_Pillar_Temple), and the strategically positioned [Bhongir Fort](/Bhongir_Fort). Each edifice tells a story, a silent narrative of the dynasties and cultures that shaped this land.

![Sri Lakshmi Narasimha Swamy Temple in Yadadri](/Sri_Lakshmi_Narasimha_Swamy_Temple,_Yadadri)
*The [Sri Lakshmi Narasimha Swamy Temple in Yadadri](/Sri_Lakshmi_Narasimha_Swamy_Temple,_Yadadri) – a place where faith, presumably, finds its solace.*

### Literacy

According to the somewhat aged [2011 census](/2011_Census_of_India), [Telangana](/Telangana)'s overall literacy rate stood at 66.46%. A closer look reveals a predictable disparity: male literacy was recorded at 74.95%, while female literacy lagged significantly at 57.92%. For those who appreciate the extremes, [Hyderabad district](/Hyderabad_district,_India) boasted the highest literacy rate at 80.96%, a stark contrast to [Mahabubnagar district](/Mahabubnagar_district), which registered the lowest at 56.06%.

More recent data from a 2019 report, "Key Indicators of Household Social Consumption on Education in India," compiled by the Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation, paints a rather concerning picture. It indicates that [Telangana](/Telangana) has a literacy rate of 72.8%, placing it as the fourth lowest among large states. Furthermore, it holds the unenviable distinction of having the second lowest literacy rate among rural women, a mere 53.7%. The report also noted that only 37.1% of the population aged 3–35 years received free education at pre-primary and higher levels in [Telangana](/Telangana). These figures suggest that, despite the passage of time, significant challenges in educational access and attainment persist, particularly for vulnerable demographics.

## Administrative divisions

*   Main articles: [List of districts of Telangana](/List_of_districts_of_Telangana), [List of revenue divisions in Telangana](/List_of_revenue_divisions_in_Telangana), and [List of mandals in Telangana](/List_of_mandals_in_Telangana)

![Telangana at the time of formation on 2 June 2014](/Telangana_at_the_time_of_formation_on_2_June_2014)
*A map of [Telangana](/Telangana) as it was at its inception on 2 June 2014. One must appreciate the effort that goes into drawing new lines on a map, even if the underlying realities often remain stubbornly complex.*

The state of [Telangana](/Telangana) is meticulously carved into [33 administrative districts](/List_of_districts_in_Telangana), a number that reflects ongoing efforts to optimize governance and bring administration closer to the populace. The two most recent additions to this roster, Mulugu and Narayanpet, were formally established on 17 February 2019, demonstrating a continuous process of recalibration. These districts are further subdivided into [70 revenue divisions](/List_of_revenue_divisions_in_Telangana), which, in turn, are meticulously broken down into [584 mandals](/List_of_mandals_in_Telangana). Collectively, the state encompasses a grand total of 10,909 revenue villages, each representing a fundamental unit of local administration.

At each tier of this intricate administrative hierarchy, specific officials are entrusted with governance. Every district is overseen by a [District Collector](/District_magistrate), a powerful figure responsible for revenue administration and maintaining law and order. Each revenue division is headed by a [Revenue Divisional Officer](/Sub-divisional_magistrate), who acts as a crucial link between the district and the local level. The mandal, a key administrative unit, is managed by a [Mandal Revenue Officer](/Tehsildar). Finally, at the grassroots level, each [village](/Revenue_Village) within every mandal is administered by a [Village Revenue Officer](/Village_accountant) (VRO), who operates under the direct supervision of the Tahsildar (MRO), ensuring that the machinery of government reaches even the most remote corners.

